 … express approval needed for staff sack The Central Bank of Nigeria said, on Sunday, that it had reached an agreement with Deposit Money Banks that none of them would retrench staff as a result of the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic on the economy. Director, Corporfor, in a statement, said that this was a fall-out of a special Bankers Committee meeting, convened on Saturday, to review the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the economy. However, fears that some banks will still go ahead with their planned retrenchment were not totally eroded as the CBN also pointed out that if it became imperative to sack workers, the bank in question must obtain express approval of the apex bank. The Point had exclusively reported that the apex bank warned Nigerians against creating panic in the banking sector through negative reports about the effects of the pandemic on the sector’s operations. Okorafor said, “A special meeting of the Bankers’ Committee was convened on May 2, 2020, to further review the implications of the COVID-19 pandemic on the Nigerian banking industry. The Committee particularly deliberated on the issue of the operating costs of banks in view of the disruptions emanating from the global economic difficulties and decided as follows: “In order to help minimise and mitigate the negative impact of the COVID19 pandemic on families and livelihoods, no bank in Nigeria shall retrench or lay-off any staff of any cadre (including full-time and part-time).” He added, “To giv2 He added, “To give effect to the above measure, the express approval of the Central Bank of Nigeria shall be required in the event that it becomes absolutely necessary to lay-off any such staff. “The Central Bank of Nigeria solicits the support of all in our collective effort to weather through the economic challenges occasioned by the COVID-19 pandemic.” 